The paper presents an automated feedback tool for novice programmers that uses supervised classification to match compilation errors in new code submissions with relevant pre-existing errors. This involves training a dense neural network on a large dataset of error-repair code examples. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category. Additionally, the use of machine learning techniques such as supervised classification and dense neural networks suggests that the paper could also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. The focus on providing feedback to novice programmers suggests that the paper could also belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The use of natural language processing techniques to match errors with relevant solutions could also place the paper in the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category. Finally, the use of machine learning to generate targeted examples for specific errors could also place the paper in the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category.
